  "summary": "# ATX Review — Issue #795 Phase 3 (load_hosts pruning)\n\n**Specialists activated**: lifecycle-core · security-reviewer · test-coverage  \n**Aggregate rating: 3/5** — no blockers, but test-coverage speci...",
  "feedback": "# ATX Review — Issue #795 Phase 3 (load_hosts pruning)\n\n**Specialists activated**: lifecycle-core · security-reviewer · test-coverage  \n**Aggregate rating: 3/5** — no blockers, but test-coverage specialist found four meaningful warning-level gaps that should be addressed before merge.\n\n---\n\n## Rating Breakdown\n\n| Specialist | Rating | Blockers | Warnings |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| lifecycle-core | 4/5 | 0 | 0 |\n| security-reviewer | 4/5 | 0 | 0 |\n| test-coverage | 3/5 | 0 | 4 |\n\n---\n\n## No Blockers\n\nAll three specialists confirmed the implementation is correct:\n- `_prune_agent_config_mirror()` correctly strips only the three Group A keys via `config.pop(key, None)` — Group B (`gateway`, `dashboard`, `api_server`) is preserved by construction, not by exclusion logic.\n- The function is idempotent: `dict.pop(key, None)` on an already-absent key is a no-op.\n- In-place mutation is safe because `load_hosts()` re-parses JSON on every call — no shared-reference hazard.\n- All defensive `isinstance(…, dict)` guards are present and correct.\n- Placement after `_apply_legacy_defaults` and `_ensure_addresses` is safe (neither prior step writes to `config`).\n- CHANGELOG entry is accurate and appropriately scoped.\n\n---\n\n## Warnings\n\n### W1 — No negative-list guard on `_PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS` *(security-reviewer + lifecycle-core)*\nA future maintainer adding `\"gateway\"` or `\"dashboard\"` to `_PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS` would silently wipe bearer tokens on load, with no test failure until a real hosts.json is affected.\n\n**Recommended fix** (module-level, one line):\n```python\nassert not (set(_PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS) \u0026 {\"gateway\", \"dashboard\", \"api_server\"}), \\\n    \"Group B keys must never appear in _PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS\"\n```\nOr add a dedicated unit test asserting the intersection is empty.\n\n### W2 — Defensive `isinstance` branches in `_prune_agent_config_mirror` are untested *(test-coverage + lifecycle-core)*\nThe `if not isinstance(record, dict): continue` (line ~301) and `if not isinstance(config, dict): continue` (line ~304) branches have zero test coverage. A refactor that drops either guard would crash silently on malformed hosts.json with no signal.\n\n**Recommended fix**: Add two tests:\n```python\n# agents with non-dict record\n_write_hosts(config_dir, [_host_with_agents({\"demo\": None, \"real\": {...}})])\n# agent with missing/None config\n_write_hosts(config_dir, [_agent_with_config(None)])\n```\nBoth should assert `load_hosts()` doesn't raise and the non-matching records pass through untouched.\n\n### W3 — No multi-agent or multi-host fan-out test *(test-coverage)*\nEvery test writes a single-host, single-agent fixture. A regression in the `agents.values()` loop that only processes the first agent, or a list comprehension bug that only prunes `data[0]`, would pass the full suite.\n\n**Recommended fix**: Add one test with 2 hosts × 3 agents (mix of Group A + Group B only + clean), asserting each agent config independently.\n\n### W4 — Three single-key strip tests should be `@pytest.mark.parametrize` *(test-coverage)*\n`test_load_hosts_strips_config_provider`, `_providers`, and `_channels` are near-identical; project convention requires parametrized table-driven tests for this pattern. Not a correctness issue, but a convention violation.\n\n**Recommended fix**: Collapse into:\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"stripped_key,stripped_value,preserved_key,preserved_value\", [\n    (\"provider\", {\"name\": \"openai\", ...}, \"gateway\", {\"port\": 40000, \"auth\": \"tok\"}),\n    (\"providers\", [...], \"dashboard\", {\"port\": 45000}),\n    (\"channels\", {...}, \"api_server\", {\"port\": 41000}),\n])\ndef test_load_hosts_strips_group_a_key(...):\n    ...\n```\n\n---\n\n## Suggestions (non-blocking, optional)\n\n| # | Source | Note |\n|---|---|---|\n| S1 | security-reviewer | `cli/status.py:176` reads `config.get(\"provider\", {}).get(\"type\")` for the status-table \"Provider\" column — will silently regress to `\"-\"` post-prune. Track as follow-up; re-source from `providers.json`. |\n| S2 | security-reviewer | Document in CHANGELOG or migration note that `channels` token residue persists on-disk until the next `save_hosts()` round-trip. The current wording covers it but could be more explicit. |\n| S3 | security-reviewer | Add a code comment near the `load_hosts()` comprehension that the function must remain non-caching — memoizing it in future would re-introduce the shared-reference mutation hazard. |\n| S4 | lifecycle-core | Optional `logger.debug(...)` when at least one key is actually pruned, to assist operator debugging on first post-upgrade load. |\n| S5 | test-coverage | Extend idempotency test to also cover a Group-A-free input (verifies pruning doesn't introduce key-ordering churn in `save_hosts`). |\n\n---\n\n## Verdict\n\n**Shippable after addressing W2 and W3** (add missing branch tests + multi-host fan-out). W1 (negative-list guard) is strongly recommended but can land in the same commit as a one-liner. W4 (parametrize) should be resolved per project convention. S1 (cli/status.py) should be filed as a follow-up before the next release to avoid a silent UI regression.\n\nNo security concerns, no correctness issues in the implementation itself.",
