s_handles_agent_without_config_key` writing an agent record with no `config` field and assert the record round-trips identically. Also add a variant with `\\\"config\\\": None` to lock down the isinstance guard.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_hosts.py (missing)\",\n      \"issue\": \"No test covers a single host containing multiple agents where only some have Group A keys. The loop at hosts.py:300 iterates `agents.values()`; a regression that breaks after the first agent (or mutates only the first) would not be detected by any existing test — all use the single `demo` agent fixture.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add a test with `agents: {\\\"a\\\": \u003chas provider+gateway\u003e, \\\"b\\\": \u003conly gateway\u003e, \\\"c\\\": \u003chas channels+dashboard\u003e}` and assert each agent's config independently with exact equality.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_hosts.py (missing)\",\n      \"issue\": \"No test covers multiple host entries in the top-level list. The list comprehension at hosts.py:81-85 prunes every host, but every test writes a single-element list. A regression that only processes `data[0]` would pass the entire suite.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add `test_load_hosts_prunes_across_multiple_hosts` with two hosts each carrying Group A residue, or fold it into the multi-agent test.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_hosts.py:46-121\",\n      \"issue\": \"`test_load_hosts_strips_config_provider`, `_providers`, and `_channels` are three near-identical tests differing only in the key under test and the Group B sibling. Project convention prefers `pytest.mark.parametrize` for table-driven cases like this.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Collapse into a single `@pytest.mark.parametrize(\\\"stripped_key, stripped_value, preserved_key, preserved_value\\\", [...])` test. Reduces ~75 lines to ~25