      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 4,\n  \"summary\": \"Narrowly-scoped destructive normalizer that strips legacy `config.{provider,providers,channels}` mirror keys on load. Constant is tight, tests cover Group-B byte-for-byte preservation and idempotent round-trip, and no downstream security check depends on the stripped keys. One display-only consumer in cli/status.py will silently degrade, and the in-memory prune does not scrub the on-disk secret residue until the next save_hosts() — both are acknowledged behaviors, not regressions.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/hosts.py:283\",\n      \"issue\": \"`_PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS` is a flat tuple with no static guard against accidental Group-B inclusion. The user's stated risk (#3) — a future maintainer adding 'gateway' or 'dashboard' to the list — would silently delete bearer tokens on the next load with no test failure beyond the existing fixture coverage.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add a module-level assertion (or unit test) of the form `assert not (set(_PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS) \u0026 {'gateway','dashboard','api_server'})` so any future widening trips immediately, not on a customer's hosts.json.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/cli/status.py:176 (out-of-diff consumer)\",\n      \"issue\": \"`cli/status.py:176` still reads `claw_record.get('config',{}).get('provider',{}).get('type')` for the status-table 'Provider' column. After this prune lands, that column will read '-' for every agent regardless of attachment state. Not a security issue (display-only, no auth gating), but flagging because the user asked about downstream readers; the audit on lifecycle/lifecycle_canonical/gui-routes came back clean but cli/status.py is also a consumer.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Re-source the provider column from `providers.json` via `provider_attachments` (the same canonical path `build_render_inputs` uses). Out-of-scope for this PR; track as follow-up.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/hosts.py:286-308\",\n      \"issue\": \"The prune is a load-time normalizer only — it strips secrets like `channels.discord.bot_token` from the in-memory dict but does NOT rewrite hosts.json. Legacy `bot_token`/`app_token` strings remain on disk (mode 0o600, owner-readable) until the next `save_hosts()` round-trip happens incidentally during some lifecycle op. The docstring's 'shrinks naturally on the next save round-trip' is honest, but the security floor is unchanged: anyone with file access could already read these tokens, and #794 stopped writing them. No regression, just not a scrubber.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"If a hard scrub is desired, have `load_hosts()` detect a non-empty prune delta and trigger a write-through (under `_hosts_lock`) the first time. Optional; the file-permissions gate is the real boundary here.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/hosts.py:80-85\",\n      \"issue\": \"Concern #1 (in-place mutation of secrets through shared references) is empirically safe because `load_hosts()` re-parses JSON on every call — there is no caching layer and no module-global cache of host dicts. Every caller gets a fresh dict tree, so `config.pop()` cannot race with any previously-issued reference. Worth documenting because it is the load order that makes this safe; introducing a future memoization on load_hosts() (a common optimization temptation) would re-introduce the exact hazard the user named.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add a one-line comment near the comprehension at hosts.py:80-85 stating that load_hosts() must remain non-caching for prune safety, or — better — add a regression test that calls load_hosts() twice and asserts the returned dicts are not the same object.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Add a Gr